pr_body:
Without it all nodes with non-ascii characters in naming look incorrect. You can download sources of WebDAV TC plugin using [this link](http://www.ghisler.com/plugins.htm) and find the mistake in file davfunc.cpp on line 2663:
```cpp
if (p) {
	p+=9;
	while (p[0]=='"' || p[0]==' ' || p[0]=='\r' || p[0]=='\n' || p[0]=='\t')
		p++;
	if (strnicmp(p,"utf-8",5)==0)
		return BODY_UTF8;
}
```
So plugin couldn't detect correct charset because it depends on "utf-8" string in first XML tag but lxml.etree object generates xml structure with only single quotes and TC WebDAV plugin doesn't understand it.

This modification attempts to solve the issue #58 by including the signals module within \__init\__.py

Now to use a Flask-User signal, simply import it from the `flask.ext.user` namespace:

    from flask.ext.user import user_logged_in, user_logged_out

    @user_logged_in.connect_via(app)
    def logged_in(sender, user, **extra):
        sender.logger.info("USER LOGGED IN")

This PR fixes the following scenario:

JSON schema:
<pre>
{
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
	"foo": {
	    "oneOf": [
		{
		    "type": "null"
		},
		{
		    "type": "array",
		    "items": {
			"type": "number"
		    }
		}
	    ]
	}
    }
}
</pre>

JSON object:

<pre>
{
    "foo": null
}
</pre>

JSON path: `$.foo.[0]`

Builder methods (that methods used by @genty_deferred) can now
return single parameters. Previous they always needed to
return a list or tuple. Thus, what used to have to be this:

   def builder(...):
      return (single_value,)

   @genty_deferred(builder)
   def test_method(...):
      ...

Can now be this:

   def builder(...):
      return single_value

   @genty_deferred(builder)
   def test_method(...):
      ...

Lifted from `tests.test_traitlets.TestValidationHook.test_dynamic_parity_trait`

```python
from traitlets import HasTraits, Int, Enum, TraitError

def _even_validator(proposal):
    name,value,owner = proposal.values()
    if owner.parity == 'even' and value % 2:
        raise TraitError('Expected an even number')
    return value

def _odd_validator(proposal):
    name,value,owner = proposal.values()
    if owner.parity == 'odd' and (value % 2 == 0):
        raise TraitError('Expected an odd number')
    return value

class Parity(HasTraits):

    value = Int()

    def _value_default(self):
        if self.parity == 'even':
            return 0
        else:
            return 1

    parity = Enum(['odd', 'even'], read_only=True)

    def __new__(cls, parity):
        p = cls.parity.validate(None,parity)
        prefix = p[0].upper()+p[1:].lower()
        suffix = cls.__name__
        klass = type(prefix+suffix,(cls,),{})
        return super(Parity, klass).__new__(klass)

    def __init__(self, parity):
        self._trait_values['parity'] = parity
        if parity=='even':
            self.register_validator(_even_validator,'value')
        if parity=='odd':
            self.register_validator(_odd_validator,'value')

o = Parity('odd')
o.value = 1
try:
    o.value = 2
except TraitError:
    pass
else:
    raise

e = Parity('even')
e.value = 2
try:
    e.value = 1
except TraitError:
    pass
else:
    raise
```

